<!-- .SH "NAME" -->
<A name=>

     <H3>NAME</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
ccs-notifyd - policy violation notification daemon for TOMOYO Linux
<!-- .SH "SYNOPSIS" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=1>

     <H3>SYNOPSIS</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- .B ccs-notifyd -->
<B>ccs-notifyd</B> <!-- .SH "DESCRIPTION" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>DESCRIPTION</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
This program detects policy violations that occur in domains set to enforcing mode and notifies the system administrator. The notification method can for example be by sending a mail, but any command can be specified in the configuration file, which is found at <I>/etc/ccs/tools/notifyd.conf</I>. This makes it possible to be notified about policy violations as soon as possible, and allows subsequent action to be taken within a short period of time.
<!-- .SH "EXAMPLES" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>EXAMPLES</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- .B Send a mail with a minimum interval of 60 seconds: -->
<B>Send a mail with a minimum interval of 60 seconds:</B> <!-- .nf -->
<PRE>
time_to_wait 0
action_to_take mail -s Notification\040from\040ccs-notifyd root@localhost
minimal_interval 60
<!-- .fi -->
</PRE>
<!-- .sp -->
<P>
Further syntax information can be found in the configuration file.
<!-- .SH "NOTES" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>NOTES</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
This program should be started from the appropriate stage during startup, for example in <I>/etc/rc.local</I>.
<!-- .sp -->
<P>
If you wish to freeze a process using the <I>time_to_wait</I> directive, then this program must be registered in <I>/proc/ccs/manager</I>.
